        secs: ['Pound Reservoir to Breaks Gorge — approach', 'Breaks Canyon — Class IV–V+, 8 mi, no exits', 'Below Breaks to Kentucky — Class III, lower river'],
        history: [
          { era: 'native', entries: [{ yr: 'Pre-contact', title: "Cherokee and Shawnee — The Breaks of the Mountains", text: "The Breaks Canyon was a boundary zone between Cherokee and Shawnee territory. 'The Breaks' — where the river cuts through Pine Mountain — was known to Native peoples as a significant geological landmark. Daniel Boone passed through in the 1770s and called it one of the most striking natural features he had seen.", src: 'Virginia Department of Historic Resources; Breaks Interstate Park' }] },
          { era: 'logging', entries: [{ yr: '1920s–1970s', title: 'Pound Dam and the Coal Era', text: "Pound Dam was constructed in 1966 by the Army Corps of Engineers to reduce flooding in the coal-mining communities downstream. The dam also created the controlled releases that now enable the Russell Fork's fall whitewater season.", src: 'USACE; Dickenson County Historical Society' }] },
          { era: 'modern', entries: [{ yr: '2023', title: 'Russell Fork Fall Festival — East Coast Extreme Kayaking', text: "The Russell Fork Fall Festival each October draws elite kayakers from across the country for the dam-release season. USACE coordinated October releases have created one of the most anticipated events on the eastern extreme kayaking calendar.", src: 'American Whitewater; Breaks Interstate Park (2023)' }] },
        ],
