        secs: ['Upper Russell — Adair County, Class I–II, spring-fed headwaters', 'Middle Russell — Class I, pastoral farmland', 'Lower Russell to Green River — Class I, confluence'],
        history: [
          { era: 'native', entries: [{ yr: 'Pre-contact', title: "Cherokee and Shawnee — Cave Country Creek", text: "The Russell Creek watershed lies within the karst landscape of south-central Kentucky — a region honeycombed with caves and springs that attracted Native peoples for shelter and the abundant game drawn to the springs. The region was contested Cherokee and Shawnee hunting territory.", src: 'Kentucky Archaeological Survey; Adair County Historical Society' }] },
          { era: 'modern', entries: [{ yr: '2023', title: 'Karst Springs — Cold-Water Refuge', text: "Russell Creek\"s spring-fed flow makes it one of the most consistent small streams in central Kentucky. The limestone springs maintain water temperatures below 65°F in summer, supporting a coldwater fish community unusual for this latitude. The creek is increasingly recognized as an important tributary to the Green River watershed.", src: 'Kentucky Division of Water; Green River Conservancy (2023)' }] },
        ],
